            <h1>FoodHub Logic</h1>
            <h2>The Logic Behind the UI</h2>
            <div style="margin-top: 40px; text-align: left; display: inline-block;">
                <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Making the website dynamic and interactive.</p>
                <h3>What this script does:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Loads restaurant data.</li>
                    <li>Handles the Shopping Cart (Add/Remove items).</li>
                    <li>Manages "Dark Mode".</li>
                    <li>Handles filtering and search.</li>
                    <li>Shows popups (Modals) for menus and checkout.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 3: Data Source -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>The Data Source</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> We are simulating a database using a JavaScript Array.
            </div>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Variable:</strong> <code>const restaurantsData</code></li>
                <li><strong>Structure:</strong> A list (Array) of Objects.</li>
                <li><strong>What's inside?</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Restaurant details (Name, Rating, Image).</li>
                        <li><strong>Nested Menu:</strong> Another list inside each restaurant containing specific food
                            items.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <pre><code><span class="comment">// Simplified Example</span>
<span class="keyword">const</span> restaurantsData = [
  {
     name: <span class="string">"Pizza Paradise"</span>,
     menu: [ { name: <span class="string">"Margherita"</span>, price: 299 } ]
  }
];</code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 4: Rendering -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>Rendering the UI</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> Taking raw data and turning it into visible HTML.
            </div>
            <h3>Function: <code>renderRestaurants()</code></h3>
            <p><strong>How it works:</strong></p>
            <ol style="margin-left: 20px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #ccc; line-height: 1.8;">
                <li>It looks at the <code>restaurantsData</code> array.</li>
                <li>It uses <code>.map()</code> to loop through every restaurant.</li>
                <li>It creates a string of HTML (divs, images, text) for each one.</li>
                <li>It injects this HTML into the page using <code>.innerHTML</code>.</li>
            </ol>
            <p style="margin-top: 20px; color: var(--secondary-accent);"><strong>Result:</strong> You see a grid of
                restaurant cards without writing HTML for each one manually.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 5: Cart Logic -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>Shopping Cart Logic</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> Tracking what the user wants to buy.
            </div>
            <p><strong>State:</strong> <code>let cart = []</code> (Starts as an empty list).</p>
            <h3>Key Functions:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><code>addToCart(id)</code>: Checks if item exists. If yes, quantity +1. If no, add to array.</li>
                <li><code>removeFromCart(id)</code>: Deletes the item from the array.</li>
                <li><code>updateCart()</code>: <strong>Crucial Function.</strong> It recalculates the Total Price and
                    updates the HTML in the sidebar.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 6: Interaction -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>User Interaction</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> Helping the user find what they want quickly.
            </div>
            <h3>Filter Chips</h3>
            <p>When you click "Fast Delivery" or "Top Rated", the code runs <code>.filter()</code> on the data array to
                show only matching restaurants.</p>
            <h3>Search Bar Logic</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Listens for the <code>click</code> or <code>Enter</code> key.</li>
                <li>Converts text to <strong>lowercase</strong> (to match easily).</li>
                <li>Checks if the <em>Restaurant Name</em> OR <em>Cuisine</em> matches your text.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 7: Modals -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>Modals (Popups)</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> Showing content without leaving the page.
            </div>
            <h3>Types of Modals:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Menu Modal:</strong> Shows food items when clicking a restaurant.</li>
                <li><strong>Auth Modal:</strong> Login/Signup forms.</li>
                <li><strong>Order Summary:</strong> The receipt shown after checkout.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3 style="margin-top: 20px;">Logic: CSS Classes</h3>
            <p>The code simply adds or removes a CSS class called <code>.active</code>.</p>
            <p
                style="text-align: center; margin-top: 10px; font-family: monospace; background: #333; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
                .active class = Popup Visible <br> No class = Popup Hidden
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 8: Dark Mode -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h2>Dark Mode</h2>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <strong>Concept:</strong> Remembering user preferences.
            </div>
            <h3>Storage</h3>
            <p>We use <code>localStorage</code>. This saves the user's choice inside their browser so it remembers them
                next time.</p>
            <h3>Logic Flow:</h3>
            <ol style="margin-left: 20px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #ccc; line-height: 1.8;">
                <li>When page loads, check if <code>darkMode</code> is "true".</li>
                <li>If yes, add the <code>.dark-mode</code> class to the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code>.</li>
                <li>Switch the icon from Sun to Moon.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <!-- Navigation Controls -->
        <div class="controls">
            <button id="prevBtn">Previous</button>
            <button id="nextBtn">Next</button>
        </div>
        <div class="slide-number" id="slideNum">1 / 8</div>
        <div class="progress-bar" id="progress"></div>

    </div>

    <script>
        const slides = document.querySelectorAll('.slide');
        const prevBtn = document.getElementById('prevBtn');
        const nextBtn = document.getElementById('nextBtn');
        const slideNum = document.getElementById('slideNum');
        const progressBar = document.getElementById('progress');
        let currentSlide = 0;

        function showSlide(index) {
            // Handle Bounds
            if (index < 0) index = 0;
            if (index >= slides.length) index = slides.length - 1;
            currentSlide = index;

            // Update UI
            slides.forEach((slide, i) => {
                slide.classList.remove('active', 'prev');
                if (i === currentSlide) {
                    slide.classList.add('active');
                } else if (i < currentSlide) {
                    slide.classList.add('prev');
                }
            });

            // Update Counter & Progress
            slideNum.textContent = `${currentSlide + 1} / ${slides.length}`;
            progressBar.style.width = `${((currentSlide + 1) / slides.length) * 100}%`;
        }

        // Event Listeners
        prevBtn.addEventListener('click', () => showSlide(currentSlide - 1));
        nextBtn.addEventListener('click', () => showSlide(currentSlide + 1));

        // Keyboard Navigation
        document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
            if (e.key === 'ArrowRight' || e.key === ' ') {
                showSlide(currentSlide + 1);
            } else if (e.key === 'ArrowLeft') {
                showSlide(currentSlide - 1);
            }
        });

        // Initial Load
        showSlide(0);
    </script>

